# Compas Reference
# Time signature: 4/4 (Cuban/Latin influence)
# Character: Festive, party vibe, accessible, danceable
# Rumba Flamenca borrows from Cuban rumba but uses Phrygian harmony
# Often heard in Gipsy Kings style

# Scale Reference
# A Phrygian Dominant (5th mode of D harmonic minor)
# A-Bb-C#-D-E-F-G
# Bright, exotic sound from the major 3rd (C#)
# More "major" feeling than natural Phrygian

# Zone-Tritone Connection
# bII -> I (Bb -> A) is the Phrygian Gravity Cell
# A=9(Z2), Bb=10(Z1) -- ZONE CROSS = resolution direction
# Latin clave patterns reinforce this gravitational pulse

# Harmony Reference
# Key: A Phrygian Dominant
# Typical progression: A - G - F - E (Andalusian with A major tonic)
# Or: A - Dm - Bb - A (emphasizing bII gravity)
# The A major chord gives brightness; Bb gives exotic tension

# Technique Reference
# Right-hand: Rasgueado (fan strum), golpe (tap), rumba strum pattern
# Often uses ventilador (fan) rasgueado on accents
# Percussive muting between strums

